Description: What a hilly and windy race!!! 2 guys went out super hard! We thought they were going to die out until Porter told me around 3 miles in that one of them was a 1:02 half marathon guy. I then decided to lead the pack. Me and the Iowa Western guys decided to work together and get them. I took the lead and started hammering. No one else was taking the lead so I told them, ‚Äú we can catch these guys.‚Äù I lead for the next 8-9 miles and then I started feeling sick and fatigued. I caught a bug last night so no surprise. At mile 10, Mohammed and I from Iowa Western started trading leads, as the pace got more aggressive. The hills were ungoing but I just prayed. The wind started taking off, Mohammad and I started pushing each other until we broke so far away I couldn‚Äôt see any one else but one guy. Although I took 3rd, this race was one of my favourites because it taught me a lot. I was able to run fast and see God‚Äôs grace when things got tough. This was one of the races that challenged me hard and had me question if I really wanted this. At mile 11, I was cooked but God told me to use my Spiritual legs to get me through. Wanting to stay in it with my team helped a lot. I tried to run the tangents smart and I think it payed off in a positive way. It‚Äôs crazy to say that my college career is officially over. I PR‚Äôd by 35 seconds in the half as this is only my 2nd one ever and to do this 3 days after racing a gutsy and gritty 8k at Nationals while feeling a little sick, I my truly blessed. Congrats to Iowa on their win! I‚Äôm pleased to announce that I‚Äôm officially going pro and I have my first pro race in just a little over a week, so my season is still going. I‚Äôm excited to gear up and I‚Äôm grateful for God and Coach Wood for believing in me, not giving up on me and opening these doors for me to continue running. I‚Äôm grateful to come from a great team at SLCC and we are still  and always #NYTJ. Thanks for everyone on here for supporting me and helping me get this far. I love you all. JQ officially signing off from JUCO!! ‚ù§Ô∏è

Activity Name: Half Marathon Championships tomorrow. Also my race recap from Saturday is below ‚¨áÔ∏è:)) You might wanna read this one;)
Description: Sorry, it‚Äôs been busy. Race recap from Saturday: I got out well, but my mindset was conservative and to just trust. The pack was aggressive, (there were lots of tugging, bumping, elbowing, tripping, Michael got spiked). I kept trying to get good positioning but I got boxed in multiple times. I stayed calm and just hung in until I could find a good position. At the next 2k loop (mid race), a guy stepped on my heel and my shoe came off. Fortunately, my teammate Michael Amitava Maiorano was in the leading pack as well and I asked him what to do. He said, ‚ÄúYou got this, I believe in you‚Äù I prayed and asked God what to do, so I felt the Spirit tell me calmly, ‚ÄúPut your shoe on; God will help you get back up there.‚Äù If you were watching it on TV,  (I got a few messages from you guys asking if I got hurt, and I didn‚Äôt, it was because I lost my shoe.) haha:) I followed as the Spirit said and I put my shoe on and kept going. With about 2 minutes of consistency, I was able to find my way back to where I was. I took it easy from here, I wanted to stay consistent to conserve energy, but also be willing to move if a surge was made, I could feel it coming. Michael was still there with me in the leading pack and we just worked together and motivated each other. Getting near the final 1k mark, though it strung out a little, there were still a lot of guys in the leading pack. I tucked myself behind Renoh as best as I could from Iowa Western; however, the pack still wasn‚Äôt letting me in. I wanted to handle the tangents as best as I could, but I knew I would have to just run on the outside out of fear of being boxed in or loosing my shoe again. So I did the extra work, then made a tiny surge to get around the guys. Right afterwards, Emmanuel Otim from Butler took off out of nowhere. Renoh was the guy I was worried about and I had no idea who Emmanuel was. I had a gut feeling heading into Nationals to be prepared just because that‚Äôs the nature of JUCO. So when Emmanuel took it, I just trusted in God and my training plan from coaches and just went with it. Because I was so conservative and didn‚Äôt lead, I still had so much left in the tank. I went really hard, looked back a few times for safety, and just put my foot on the gas and gave it everything I had. Emmanuel still was coming, and coming and coming. So I kept pushing, and pushing and pushing. Mohammed El Youssfi from Odessa came out of nowhere and I didn‚Äôt realize it. So I literally just ran with everything I possibly could. It almost felt like my life was literally on the line. When I saw the finish line, I let God‚Äôs grace carry me through and I successfully defended the title. I looked right past me and saw Michael right there. I was overjoyed. Then I saw Finn, Porter Hunter, Sam and Jayden. We waited and waited to see if we won. The results kept updating. At the end, we won. Men and women. God is great, God is real. We can do anything, even during adversity. Running with the Holy Spirit and calling the Hosts of Heaven with Heavenly Father and  Jesus Christ included never fails. I know that for a fact. Currently preparing for the Half Marathon National Championships tomorrow morning.
with Jake, Josh, Kevin, and Emily.

Activity Name: Sound Running Cross Country National Championships
Description: So grateful to be here. I didn‚Äôt have my best race but I‚Äôm pretty happy. About a mile in, I underestimated how cooked I am from Nationals last week with the 8k and the Half Marathon. In the race, I started fading early in. Josh Thompson caught up to me, and said, ‚Äúrun with me.‚Äù I took that to heart and just stayed close to him as much as I possibly could. About 2 miles later, Jake Heslington caught up to me and I just tried to stay with him as long as I could. Mantz and Jared Murphy were cheering me on, and I let that carry me as best as I could. The Spirit told me, ‚Äúyou can do this.‚Äù I switched gears and started picking people off, and fading again. And picking people off, and fading again. I fought to the finish line. My legs are just cooked. Shoutout to my agent for flying out to see my first race. The Hay Bales were fun each mile. If anything, I am grateful to get to be here. I got to experience the dream as a pro for the first time. I learned that I truly belong here and I can do this. I‚Äôm excited to get to take a much needed break for my mental and physical. And I‚Äôm happy to be surrounded by the people I am. God is great. I‚Äôm excited for this reset. Shoutout to Jake, Kevin and Josh for being absolute dogs on our team today, and to all of the women. Emily, Mica, Aubrey, Maddie and Kode :) I‚Äôm grateful to God for this experience and to be able to feel so much joy in my heart. He has truly given me so much mercy and grace throughout my entire time running, and I can see it even more so now. I‚Äôve also learned so much from this race. So many things that I can take with me in my next pro races. If you want to know what‚Äôs next for me, stay tuned with a super sweet and special interview I just did with Flo Track.
